      • test_sparql11_sum_02

        public void test_sparql11_sum_02()
                          throws Exception
        This is not a DAWG test. There is no data for the aggregation. Sesame is expecting a solution set consisting of a single solution with 0^^xsd:integer. We are producing an empty solution set, which is the correct result. The expected answer has been modified here so the test will pass, but it will still fail in the Sesame test suite until they fix the issue in their test manifest.

        See http://www.openrdf.org/issues/browse/SES-884 (Aggregation with an solution set as input should produce an empty solution as output)

        Throws:
        Exception

        test_two_nested_opt
        

        public void test_two_nested_opt()
                         throws Exception
        

        Nested Optionals - 1. Badly designed left join with TWO
 optionals.
 
 
         SELECT *
 { 
     :x1 :p ?v .
     OPTIONAL
     {
       :x3 :q ?w .
       OPTIONAL { :x2 :p ?v }
     }
 }
 
        
 
 Note: Because this is a badly designed left join, it is translated into a
 named subquery. However, the translated query will fail if the "OPTIONAL"
 semantics are not being attached to the INCLUDE.
        

        

        Throws:
        

        Exception
        

        See Also:
        

        ASTBottomUpOptimizer

        test_opt_complex_2
        

        public void test_opt_complex_2()
                        throws Exception
        

        Complex optional semantics: 2 (dawg-optional-complex-2).
 
 
         Complex optional: LeftJoin(Join(BGP(..),Graph(var,{..})),Union(..,..))
 
        
 
 
         PREFIX  foaf:   
 PREFIX    ex:   
 SELECT ?id ?ssn
 WHERE 
 { 
     ?person 
         a foaf:Person;
         foaf:name ?name . 
     GRAPH ?x { 
         [] foaf:name ?name;
            foaf:nick ?nick
     } 
     OPTIONAL { 
         { ?person ex:empId ?id } UNION { ?person ex:ssn ?ssn } 
     } 
 }
 
        
 
 
         :dawg-optional-complex-2 a mf:QueryEvaluationTest ;
     mf:name    "Complex optional semantics: 2" ;
     rdfs:comment
             "Complex optional: LeftJoin(Join(BGP(..),Graph(var,{..})),Union(..,..))" ;
     dawgt:approval dawgt:Approved ;
     dawgt:approvedBy  ;
     mf:action
     [ qt:query   ;
       qt:graphData ;
       qt:data    ] ;
     mf:result   .

 }

        This is sesame TCK test sparql11-subquery-04. We picked it
 up with Sesame 2.6.3. It fails in the TCK run, but it appears to be Ok
 when run at this layer.

 test_sparql11_order_02().

         PREFIX ex: 
 SELECT ?friend
 WHERE {
   ?popular ex:knows ?friend .
   {
     SELECT ?popular
     WHERE {
       ?someone ex:knows ?popular
     } 
     GROUP BY ?popular
     ORDER BY DESC(COUNT(?someone))
     LIMIT 2
   }
 }

        test_join_with_no_shared_variables
        

        public void test_join_with_no_shared_variables()
                                        throws Exception
        

        This is based on service13, which is an openrdf Federated
 Query test. The test was failing because the two SERVICE joins do not
 share any variables and use a hash join. Thus, we had two solutions from
 the first SERVICE and sent two empty solutions to the second
 SERVICE. This caused the 2nd SERVICE to deliver twice as many solutions
 as is expected. Because the hash join was not correlated through a rowId,
 we wind up wind a full cross product of both (empty) source solutions and
 all solutions coming back from the 2nd service.
 
        
 It is interesting that this test passes without modification when run on
 purely local data. This suggests that the problem is not one of bottom up
 evaluation, but the lack of a variable to correlate the result sets from
 the remote services.
 
        
 Note: This test is a rewrite of the same query to run against purely
 local data. All I did was comment out the SERVICE keyword and service
 URI.
 
 
         # Test for SES 899
 
 PREFIX :  
 PREFIX owl:  
 
 SELECT ?a ?b
 {
   #SERVICE  
   {
      ?a a ?t1 
      filter(?t1 = owl:Class) 
   }
   #SERVICE  
   { 
      ?b a ?t2 
      filter(?t2 = owl:Class) 
   } 
 }
 
        

        

        Throws:
        

        Exception
